soln_description:
Solution. We can assume without loss of generality that $p \geq q \geq r$.

Since $p \mid q+n$ and $p \mid r+n$, we have $p \mid q-r$, but $0 \leq q-r<q \leq p$, so we must have $q=r$. Furthermore, $q \mid p+n$ and $q \mid r+n$ imply $q \mid p-r=p-q$, so $q \mid p$, which is only possible if $p=q=r$.

Marking scheme

Maximum of the following points is taken:

7 p. for a complete solution;

$1 \mathrm{p}$. for proving $p \mid q-r$ and/or similar;

2 p. for proving $p \mid q-r$, where $p$ explicitly denotes the maximum of $p, q, r$;

4 p. for proving that two of the numbers are equal;

$3 \mathrm{p}$. for proving of $p=q=r$ under assumption that two of the numbers are already equal.

