soln_description:
Proof: First, perform algebraic transformation, set $a=\frac{1}{x}, b=\frac{1}{y}, c=\frac{1}{z}$, thus
$$\sqrt{\frac{1}{a}+\frac{1}{b}+\frac{1}{c}} \geqslant \sqrt{\frac{1-a}{a}}+\sqrt{\frac{1-b}{b}}+\sqrt{\frac{1-c}{c}}$$

where $a, b, c \in(0,1)$, and $a+b+c=2$. Substituting the condition $a+b+c=2$, we get that equation (3) is equivalent to
$$\begin{aligned}
& \sqrt{\frac{1}{2}(a+b+c)\left(\frac{1}{a}+\frac{1}{b}+\frac{1}{c}\right)} \\
\geqslant & \sqrt{\frac{\frac{a+b+c}{2}-a}{a}}+\sqrt{\frac{\frac{a+b+c}{2}-b}{b}}+\sqrt{\frac{\frac{a+b+c}{2}-c}{c}}
\end{aligned}$$

which is
$$\begin{aligned}
& \sqrt{(a+b+c)\left(\frac{1}{a}+\frac{1}{b}+\frac{1}{c}\right)} \\
\geqslant & \sqrt{\frac{b+c-a}{a}}+\sqrt{\frac{c+a-b}{b}}+\sqrt{\frac{a+b-c}{c}}
\end{aligned}$$

In fact, using the Cauchy-Schwarz inequality, it is easy to see that
$$\begin{aligned}
& \sqrt{[(b+c-a)+(c+a-b)+(a+b-c)]\left(\frac{1}{a}+\frac{1}{b}+\frac{1}{c}\right)} \\
\geqslant & \sqrt{\frac{b+c-a}{a}}+\sqrt{\frac{c+a-b}{b}}+\sqrt{\frac{a+b-c}{c}}
\end{aligned}$$

which means equation (4) holds.

